  // =============================================================================
  // APOPTOSIS
  // =============================================================================
  {
    id: 'apoptosis',
    subjectId: 'pathology',
    subspecialtyId: 'pathology-general',
    name: 'Apoptosis',
    slug: 'apoptosis',
    description: 'Programmed cell death, intrinsic and extrinsic pathways, regulatory mechanisms',
    content: {
      concept: `# Apoptosis - Programmed Cell Death

## Definition

> **Apoptosis** is a pathway of cell death in which cells activate enzymes that degrade their own nuclear DNA and nuclear/cytoplasmic proteins, leading to cell death without eliciting inflammatory response.

## Apoptosis vs Necrosis

| Feature | Apoptosis | Necrosis |
|---------|-----------|----------|
| **Trigger** | Physiologic or pathologic | Always pathologic |
| **Cells affected** | Single cells | Groups of cells |
| **Cell size** | Shrinkage | Swelling |
| **Nucleus** | Fragmentation | Pyknosis → karyolysis |
| **Plasma membrane** | Intact (blebs) | Disrupted |
| **Cell contents** | Intact | Released |
| **Inflammation** | None | Present |
| **Energy** | ATP-dependent | ATP-independent |

## Causes of Apoptosis

### Physiologic Apoptosis
\`\`\`
1. EMBRYOGENESIS
   ├── Removal of interdigital webs
   ├── Formation of hollow organs
   └── Deletion of vestigial structures

2. HORMONE WITHDRAWAL
   ├── Endometrial shedding (progesterone ↓)
   ├── Prostate after castration (testosterone ↓)
   └── Breast post-lactation (prolactin ↓)

3. IMMUNE SYSTEM
   ├── Deletion of autoreactive lymphocytes
   ├── Elimination of exhausted neutrophils
   └── CTL killing of virus-infected cells

4. CELL TURNOVER
   └── Intestinal crypt cells, epidermal cells
\`\`\`

### Pathologic Apoptosis
| Stimulus | Examples |
|----------|----------|
| **DNA damage** | Radiation, chemotherapy |
| **Misfolded proteins** | Neurodegenerative diseases |
| **Viral infection** | CTL-mediated killing |
| **Graft rejection** | CTL, Fas-mediated |

## Morphology of Apoptosis

### Light Microscopy
- **Cell shrinkage**
- Dense eosinophilic cytoplasm
- **Chromatin condensation**
- **Apoptotic bodies** (membrane-bound fragments)

### Electron Microscopy
- Nuclear chromatin condensation at periphery
- Cytoplasmic blebbing
- Apoptotic body formation
- Phagocytosis by macrophages (no inflammation)

> 💎 **Councilman bodies** in viral hepatitis = apoptotic hepatocytes

## Biochemical Features

1. **DNA fragmentation** at internucleosomal linker sites → 180-200 bp fragments → DNA ladder on gel electrophoresis
2. **Phosphatidylserine exposure** on outer leaflet → "eat me" signal for phagocytes
3. **Caspase activation** (cysteine aspartases) → execution of apoptosis

## Mechanisms of Apoptosis

### Caspases - The Executioners

\`\`\`
INITIATOR CASPASES:
├── Caspase-8 (extrinsic pathway)
├── Caspase-9 (intrinsic pathway)
└── Activate executioner caspases

EXECUTIONER CASPASES:
├── Caspase-3 (most important)
├── Caspase-6
├── Caspase-7
└── Execute cell death program
\`\`\`

### Intrinsic (Mitochondrial) Pathway

> Triggered by **growth factor withdrawal, DNA damage, misfolded proteins**

**Mechanism**:
\`\`\`
Cell stress/DNA damage
    ↓
p53 activation
    ↓
↑ Pro-apoptotic BCL2 proteins (BAX, BAK)
↓ Anti-apoptotic BCL2 proteins (BCL-2, BCL-XL)
    ↓
BAX/BAK oligomerize in mitochondrial membrane
    ↓
Mitochondrial outer membrane permeabilization (MOMP)
    ↓
CYTOCHROME C release
    ↓
Cytochrome C + Apaf-1 + Caspase-9 → APOPTOSOME
    ↓
Caspase-9 activation
    ↓
Caspase-3 activation → APOPTOSIS
\`\`\`

**BCL-2 Family Proteins**:
| Pro-apoptotic | Anti-apoptotic |
|---------------|----------------|
| BAX | BCL-2 |
| BAK | BCL-XL |
| BIM, BID, BAD | MCL-1 |

> 💎 **BCL-2** overexpression in follicular lymphoma → t(14;18) → resistance to apoptosis

### Extrinsic (Death Receptor) Pathway

> Triggered by **death receptor engagement** on plasma membrane

**Death Receptors** (TNF receptor family):
- **Fas (CD95)** - binds Fas ligand
- **TNFR1** - binds TNF
- **TRAIL receptors (DR4, DR5)** - binds TRAIL

**Mechanism (Fas pathway)**:
\`\`\`
FasL binding to Fas
    ↓
Fas trimerization
    ↓
Recruitment of FADD (adaptor protein)
    ↓
FADD recruits Pro-caspase-8
    ↓
DISC formation (Death-Inducing Signaling Complex)
    ↓
Caspase-8 activation
    ↓
Caspase-3 activation → APOPTOSIS
\`\`\`

### Cross-talk Between Pathways

Caspase-8 can cleave **BID → tBID** (truncated BID), which then activates BAX/BAK, linking extrinsic to intrinsic pathway.

## Regulators of Apoptosis

### Pro-apoptotic
| Factor | Function |
|--------|----------|
| **p53** | Tumor suppressor, induces BAX |
| **BAX, BAK** | Mitochondrial pore formation |
| **BID, BIM, BAD** | BH3-only activators |
| **Cytochrome c** | Apoptosome formation |

### Anti-apoptotic
| Factor | Function |
|--------|----------|
| **BCL-2, BCL-XL** | Block BAX/BAK |
| **FLIP** | Blocks caspase-8 activation |
| **IAPs** | Inhibitors of apoptosis proteins |

## Apoptosis in Disease

### Dysregulated Apoptosis (Too Little)
| Disease | Mechanism |
|---------|-----------|
| **Cancer** | BCL-2 overexpression, p53 mutations |
| **Autoimmune** | Failure to delete autoreactive lymphocytes |
| **Viral infections** | Viral proteins inhibit apoptosis (EBV, HPV) |

### Excessive Apoptosis (Too Much)
| Disease | Mechanism |
|---------|-----------|
| **Neurodegenerative** | Alzheimer's, Parkinson's, ALS |
| **Ischemic injury** | Heart, brain |
| **HIV/AIDS** | CD4+ T cell depletion |

## Detection Methods

| Method | Detects |
|--------|---------|
| **TUNEL** | DNA fragmentation (3'-OH ends) |
| **Annexin V** | Phosphatidylserine on outer membrane |
| **Caspase assays** | Activated caspases |
| **DNA ladder** | 180-200 bp fragments |`,
      keyPoints: [
        'Apoptosis = programmed cell death, ATP-dependent, NO inflammation',
        'Intrinsic pathway: Mitochondria, Cytochrome c, Caspase-9, p53-mediated',
        'Extrinsic pathway: Death receptors (Fas), DISC, Caspase-8',
        'Caspase-3 = final common executioner caspase',
        'BCL-2 family: Pro-apoptotic (BAX, BAK) vs Anti-apoptotic (BCL-2, BCL-XL)',
        'Phosphatidylserine exposure = "eat me" signal',
        'DNA ladder = 180-200 bp fragments (internucleosomal cleavage)',
        'BCL-2 overexpression in follicular lymphoma t(14;18)'
      ],
