  // =============================================================================
  // TISSUE REPAIR & HEALING
  // =============================================================================
  {
    id: 'tissue-repair-healing',
    subjectId: 'pathology',
    subspecialtyId: 'pathology-general',
    name: 'Tissue Repair & Healing',
    slug: 'tissue-repair-healing',
    description: 'Regeneration vs repair, wound healing phases, factors affecting healing',
    content: {
      concept: `# Tissue Repair & Healing

## Overview

> After injury, tissues can heal by **regeneration** (complete restoration) or **repair** (scar formation). The outcome depends on the tissue's regenerative capacity and the extent of injury.

## Regeneration vs Repair

| Feature | Regeneration | Repair (Scarring) |
|---------|--------------|-------------------|
| **Definition** | Complete restitution of tissue | Deposition of connective tissue |
| **Structure** | Normal architecture restored | Architecture altered |
| **Function** | Fully restored | May be compromised |
| **Requirement** | Intact tissue scaffold, labile/stable cells | Extensive damage, permanent cells |

## Cell Populations by Proliferative Capacity

### Labile Cells (Continuously Dividing)
- Always in cell cycle
- Examples: **Epidermis, GI epithelium, bone marrow, respiratory epithelium**
- **Excellent regenerative capacity**

### Stable Cells (Quiescent)
- In G₀, can enter cell cycle when stimulated
- Examples: **Hepatocytes, renal tubular cells, fibroblasts, smooth muscle**
- **Good regenerative capacity**

### Permanent Cells (Non-dividing)
- Cannot re-enter cell cycle
- Examples: **Neurons, cardiac myocytes, skeletal muscle**
- **Minimal regeneration; repair by scarring**

> 💎 **Liver** can regenerate up to 70% of its mass due to stable cells (hepatocytes)

## Wound Healing

### Types of Wound Healing

**Primary Intention (First Intention)**:
\`\`\`
├── Clean, surgical wound
├── Minimal tissue loss
├── Edges approximated (sutured)
├── Minimal scarring
└── Heals in 7-10 days
\`\`\`

**Secondary Intention (Second Intention)**:
\`\`\`
├── Open wound, tissue loss
├── Edges NOT approximated
├── Fills with granulation tissue
├── Significant scarring
├── Wound contraction (myofibroblasts)
└── Takes weeks to months
\`\`\`

### Phases of Wound Healing

\`\`\`
Day 0: INJURY
    │
    ▼
PHASE 1: HEMOSTASIS & INFLAMMATION (0-3 days)
    │
    ├── Immediate: Vasoconstriction, platelet plug
    ├── Hours: Vasodilation, neutrophil influx
    ├── Day 1-2: Macrophages arrive
    └── Key mediators: TGF-β, PDGF, FGF
    │
    ▼
PHASE 2: PROLIFERATION (3-14 days)
    │
    ├── Angiogenesis (VEGF, FGF)
    ├── Fibroblast migration, collagen synthesis
    ├── Granulation tissue formation
    └── Re-epithelialization
    │
    ▼
PHASE 3: REMODELING (2 weeks - 1 year)
    │
    ├── Collagen cross-linking
    ├── Type III collagen → Type I collagen
    ├── ↓ Vascularity, ↓ cellularity
    └── Maximum strength: 70-80% of original
\`\`\`

### Key Events by Day

| Timeframe | Events |
|-----------|--------|
| **Day 1** | Clot, neutrophils |
| **Day 2-3** | Macrophages, granulation tissue begins |
| **Day 3-5** | Peak granulation tissue, re-epithelialization |
| **Week 1** | Type III collagen predominates |
| **Week 2** | Collagen accumulation, ↓ vascularity |
| **Months** | Remodeling, Type I replaces Type III |

### Granulation Tissue

> Vascular, edematous connective tissue rich in vessels and fibroblasts

**Composition**:
- New capillaries (angiogenesis)
- Fibroblasts
- Loose ECM (Type III collagen, proteoglycans)
- Inflammatory cells

**Gross Appearance**: Pink, granular, bleeds easily

**Microscopic**: Small vessels, plump fibroblasts, loose matrix

> 💎 "Proud flesh" = excessive granulation tissue protruding above wound surface

## Angiogenesis

### Process
\`\`\`
1. Vasodilation (NO) + ↑ permeability (VEGF)
2. Degradation of basement membrane (MMPs)
3. Migration of endothelial cells
4. Proliferation of endothelial cells
5. Vessel maturation and pruning
\`\`\`

### Key Mediators

| Factor | Function |
|--------|----------|
| **VEGF** | Most important, ↑ permeability, EC proliferation |
| **FGF** | EC proliferation, migration |
| **Angiopoietin-1** | Vessel stabilization |
| **Angiopoietin-2** | Vessel destabilization (for sprouting) |

> 💎 **VEGF** is induced by **hypoxia** via HIF-1α

## Fibrosis & Scar Formation

### Collagen Synthesis

\`\`\`
Fibroblast
    │
    ├── TGF-β stimulus
    │
    ▼
Procollagen synthesis (RER)
    │
    ├── Hydroxylation of Pro, Lys (requires Vitamin C)
    │
    ▼
Triple helix formation
    │
    ▼
Secretion
    │
    ▼
Cleavage of propeptides
    │
    ▼
Cross-linking (lysyl oxidase, requires Cu)
    │
    ▼
Mature collagen fibers
\`\`\`

### Collagen Types

| Type | Location | Notes |
|------|----------|-------|
| **Type I** | Bone, skin, tendon | Most abundant (90%) |
| **Type II** | Cartilage | |
| **Type III** | Granulation tissue, vessels | Early wound healing |
| **Type IV** | Basement membrane | |

### Remodeling
- **Matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs)**: Degrade ECM
- **Tissue inhibitors of MMPs (TIMPs)**: Regulate MMP activity
- Balance determines net collagen accumulation

## Wound Strength

\`\`\`
Week 1: 10% of normal (fibrin, Type III collagen)
Week 3: 20% of normal
3 months: 70-80% of normal (Type I collagen)
Maximum: Never exceeds 80% of unwounded skin
\`\`\`

## Factors Affecting Wound Healing

### Local Factors

| Factor | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| **Infection** | Prolongs inflammation, delays healing |
| **Mechanical factors** | Tension, motion delay healing |
| **Foreign bodies** | Persistent inflammation |
| **Size, location** | Larger wounds heal slower |
| **Blood supply** | Poor perfusion delays healing |
| **Wound type** | Incised heals better than crush injury |

### Systemic Factors

| Factor | Effect |
|--------|--------|
| **Nutrition** | Protein, Vitamin C (collagen), Zinc |
| **Diabetes** | Impaired healing, infections |
| **Glucocorticoids** | ↓ Collagen synthesis, ↓ inflammation |
| **Infection** | Systemic sepsis impairs healing |
| **Age** | Delayed healing in elderly |

> 💎 **Vitamin C deficiency** → cannot hydroxylate proline/lysine → defective collagen → poor wound healing + scurvy

## Complications of Wound Healing

### Deficient Healing
- **Wound dehiscence**: Separation of wound edges
- **Ulceration**: Failure to epithelialize
- **Incisional hernia**: Weak scar

### Excessive Healing
| Condition | Features |
|-----------|----------|
| **Hypertrophic scar** | Raised, within wound margins, regresses |
| **Keloid** | Extends BEYOND wound margins, doesn't regress, more common in dark skin |
| **Proud flesh** | Excessive granulation tissue |

> 💎 **Keloid** = excessive Type I and III collagen extending beyond wound margins

### Contracture
- Excessive contraction in secondary intention healing
- Common in burns
- Can cause functional impairment`,
      keyPoints: [
        'Labile cells (skin, GI, marrow) = excellent regeneration; Stable cells (liver) = good; Permanent (neurons, cardiac) = scarring',
        'Primary intention = approximated edges, minimal scarring; Secondary = open wound, granulation tissue',
        'Phases: Hemostasis/Inflammation (0-3d) → Proliferation (3-14d) → Remodeling (weeks-year)',
        'Granulation tissue = new vessels + fibroblasts + Type III collagen',
        'VEGF = most important angiogenesis factor, induced by hypoxia',
        'Type III collagen (early) → Type I collagen (mature scar)',
        'Maximum wound strength = 70-80% of normal',
        'Vitamin C essential for collagen hydroxylation; Zinc for epithelialization'
      ],
