  // =============================================================================
  // HEMODYNAMIC DISORDERS
  // =============================================================================
  {
    id: 'hemodynamic-disorders',
    subjectId: 'pathology',
    subspecialtyId: 'pathology-general',
    name: 'Hemodynamic Disorders',
    slug: 'hemodynamic-disorders',
    description: 'Edema, hyperemia, congestion, hemorrhage',
    content: {
      concept: `# Hemodynamic Disorders

## Overview

> Hemodynamic disorders involve disturbances in blood flow, fluid distribution, and vascular integrity. Understanding Starling forces is fundamental to these conditions.

## Starling Forces

**Fluid Movement = (Pc - Pi) - (πc - πi)**

| Force | Direction | Normal Value |
|-------|-----------|--------------|
| **Pc** (capillary hydrostatic) | Out of vessel | 35 mmHg (arterial), 15 mmHg (venous) |
| **Pi** (interstitial hydrostatic) | Into vessel | ~0 mmHg |
| **πc** (plasma oncotic) | Into vessel | 25-28 mmHg (albumin) |
| **πi** (interstitial oncotic) | Out of vessel | ~8 mmHg |

> 💎 **Albumin** is the major determinant of plasma oncotic pressure

## Edema

> **Edema** = abnormal accumulation of fluid in interstitial spaces or body cavities

### Types of Edema

| Type | Location |
|------|----------|
| **Peripheral** | Legs (dependent) |
| **Ascites** | Peritoneal cavity |
| **Hydrothorax** | Pleural cavity |
| **Hydropericardium** | Pericardial cavity |
| **Anasarca** | Generalized severe edema |

### Pathophysiology of Edema

\`\`\`
1. ↑ HYDROSTATIC PRESSURE
   ├── Heart failure (right → peripheral, left → pulmonary)
   ├── Venous obstruction (DVT)
   ├── Cirrhosis (portal hypertension → ascites)
   └── Pregnancy, prolonged standing

2. ↓ ONCOTIC PRESSURE (Hypoalbuminemia)
   ├── Nephrotic syndrome (protein loss)
   ├── Liver disease (↓ synthesis)
   ├── Malnutrition (kwashiorkor)
   └── Protein-losing enteropathy

3. ↑ VASCULAR PERMEABILITY
   ├── Inflammation
   ├── Allergic reactions
   ├── Burns
   └── ARDS

4. LYMPHATIC OBSTRUCTION
   ├── Tumors
   ├── Surgery (mastectomy → arm lymphedema)
   ├── Filariasis → Elephantiasis
   └── Radiation

5. SODIUM RETENTION
   ├── Renal failure
   └── Secondary to ↓ renal perfusion (CHF, cirrhosis)
\`\`\`

### Characteristics of Edema Fluid

| Type | Protein | Specific Gravity | Causes |
|------|---------|------------------|--------|
| **Transudate** | <3 g/dL | <1.012 | CHF, cirrhosis, nephrotic |
| **Exudate** | >3 g/dL | >1.020 | Inflammation, infection |

### Pitting vs Non-Pitting Edema

| Pitting | Non-Pitting |
|---------|-------------|
| Indentation persists | Indentation doesn't persist |
| Low protein (transudate) | High protein (lymphedema) |
| CHF, venous, renal | Lymphedema, myxedema |

> 💎 **Myxedema** (hypothyroidism) = non-pitting due to mucopolysaccharide (hyaluronic acid) accumulation

## Hyperemia and Congestion

### Hyperemia (Active)

> **Increased blood flow** due to **arteriolar dilation**

| Features | Examples |
|----------|----------|
| Active process | Exercise, inflammation |
| Arterial blood | Erection |
| Red appearance | Blushing |

### Congestion (Passive)

> **Impaired venous drainage** leading to blood accumulation

| Features | Examples |
|----------|----------|
| Passive process | Heart failure |
| Venous blood | Venous obstruction |
| Blue-red (cyanotic) | Hepatic congestion |

**Types of Congestion**:

**Acute Pulmonary Congestion**:
- LV failure → ↑ pressure in pulmonary veins
- Engorged capillaries
- Alveolar edema
- Dyspnea, orthopnea

**Chronic Pulmonary Congestion**:
- Fibrosis of alveolar walls
- **Heart failure cells** (hemosiderin-laden macrophages)
- "Brown induration" of lung

**Acute Hepatic Congestion**:
- RV failure → ↑ central venous pressure
- Centrilobular congestion
- Hepatomegaly, tender liver

**Chronic Hepatic Congestion**:
- **Nutmeg liver** (mottled red-brown)
- Central hemorrhagic necrosis
- Zone 3 (centrilobular) most affected
- Can progress to cardiac cirrhosis

> 💎 **Nutmeg liver** = alternating pale (portal) and dark (central) areas resembling nutmeg

## Hemorrhage

> **Extravasation of blood** from vessels into tissues or body cavities

### Types by Location

| Term | Location |
|------|----------|
| **Hematoma** | Localized collection in tissue |
| **Hemothorax** | Pleural cavity |
| **Hemopericardium** | Pericardial cavity |
| **Hemoperitoneum** | Peritoneal cavity |
| **Hemarthrosis** | Joint space |

### Types by Size (Skin)

| Type | Size | Features |
|------|------|----------|
| **Petechiae** | 1-2 mm | Pinpoint, thrombocytopenia, vasculitis |
| **Purpura** | 3-10 mm | Trauma, vasculitis, amyloid |
| **Ecchymoses** | >10 mm | Bruises, trauma, coagulopathy |

### Color Changes in Bruises

\`\`\`
Fresh: Red-blue (deoxyHb)
    ↓
1-3 days: Blue-purple (biliverdin)
    ↓
3-7 days: Green (biliverdin)
    ↓
7-14 days: Yellow-brown (bilirubin, hemosiderin)
    ↓
Resolution
\`\`\`

## Significance and Clinical Effects

| Volume Loss | Effects |
|-------------|---------|
| **<20%** | Minimal, compensated |
| **20-35%** | Tachycardia, cold extremities |
| **35-50%** | Shock, oliguria |
| **>50%** | Often fatal |

### Consequences of Hemorrhage
1. **Hypovolemic shock** (if rapid, significant)
2. **Anemia** (if chronic, slow)
3. **Jaundice** (if hemorrhage in body cavity - reabsorbed bilirubin)
4. **Compression** (hematoma effect)`,
      keyPoints: [
        'Edema: ↑ hydrostatic, ↓ oncotic, ↑ permeability, lymphatic obstruction, Na retention',
        'Transudate = low protein (<3g/dL); Exudate = high protein (>3g/dL, inflammation)',
        'Pitting edema = low protein (CHF); Non-pitting = lymphedema, myxedema',
        'Hyperemia = active (arteriolar dilation); Congestion = passive (venous)',
        'Heart failure cells = hemosiderin-laden macrophages in chronic pulmonary congestion',
        'Nutmeg liver = chronic hepatic congestion (zone 3 affected)',
        'Petechiae (<2mm) = thrombocytopenia; Purpura (3-10mm); Ecchymoses (>10mm)',
        'Blood loss >35% = shock; >50% often fatal'
      ],
