  {
    id: 'shock-pathology',
    subjectId: 'pathology',
    subspecialtyId: 'pathology-general',
    name: 'Shock',
    slug: 'shock-pathology',
    description: 'Types of shock, pathogenesis, stages, organ changes',
    content: {
      concept: `# Shock

## Definition

> **Shock** is a state of systemic hypoperfusion due to reduced cardiac output or reduced effective circulating blood volume, resulting in cellular hypoxia and organ dysfunction.

## Types of Shock

### Classification

\`\`\`
SHOCK
├── CARDIOGENIC (Pump failure)
│   └── MI, arrhythmia, tamponade
│
├── HYPOVOLEMIC (Volume loss)
│   └── Hemorrhage, fluid loss
│
├── DISTRIBUTIVE (Maldistribution)
│   ├── Septic (most common cause of shock death)
│   ├── Anaphylactic
│   └── Neurogenic
│
└── OBSTRUCTIVE
    └── PE, tension pneumothorax
\`\`\`

### Hemodynamic Profiles

| Type | CO | SVR | CVP/PCWP |
|------|-----|-----|----------|
| **Cardiogenic** | ↓ | ↑ | ↑ |
| **Hypovolemic** | ↓ | ↑ | ↓ |
| **Septic (early)** | ↑ (warm) | ↓ | ↓ |
| **Septic (late)** | ↓ (cold) | ↑ | ↓ |
| **Anaphylactic** | ↓ | ↓ | ↓ |
| **Neurogenic** | ↓ | ↓ | ↓ |

> 💎 Early septic shock is **hyperdynamic** (warm, ↑CO, ↓SVR) before progressing to cold shock

## Stages of Shock

### Stage 1: Non-progressive (Compensated)

\`\`\`
↓ Blood pressure detected
    ↓
Baroreceptor reflex activation
    ↓
├── ↑ Heart rate (sympathetic)
├── ↑ Peripheral vasoconstriction
├── ↑ Renin-angiotensin-aldosterone
└── ↑ ADH secretion
    ↓
Maintained perfusion to vital organs
(Brain, Heart - "redistribution")
\`\`\`

### Stage 2: Progressive (Decompensated)

\`\`\`
Prolonged hypoperfusion
    ↓
├── Tissue hypoxia → Anaerobic metabolism
├── Lactic acidosis
├── Endothelial dysfunction
├── Capillary leak
└── DIC may develop
    ↓
Worsening organ function
Refractory to fluid resuscitation
\`\`\`

### Stage 3: Irreversible

\`\`\`
Severe cellular injury
    ↓
├── Myocardial depression
├── Vascular paralysis
├── Multi-organ failure
├── Lysosomal enzyme release
└── Complement activation
    ↓
Death despite treatment
\`\`\`

## Septic Shock

> Most common cause of death from shock in hospitals

### Pathophysiology

\`\`\`
Infection (usually Gram-negative)
    ↓
LPS (endotoxin) or Gram+ components
    ↓
Toll-like receptors (TLR4)
    ↓
Macrophage activation
    ↓
Massive cytokine release ("cytokine storm")
├── TNF-α, IL-1, IL-6
├── High-mobility group box 1 (HMGB1)
└── Complement activation
    ↓
├── Vasodilation (NO, PGI₂) → ↓ SVR
├── Endothelial dysfunction → Capillary leak
├── Myocardial depression (TNF, NO)
├── Procoagulant state → DIC
└── Metabolic abnormalities
    ↓
Multi-organ dysfunction syndrome (MODS)
\`\`\`

### Gram-Negative vs Gram-Positive

| Feature | Gram-Negative | Gram-Positive |
|---------|---------------|---------------|
| **Trigger** | LPS (endotoxin) | Lipoteichoic acid, peptidoglycan |
| **Receptor** | TLR4 | TLR2 |
| **Superantigens** | No | Yes (Toxic shock) |
| **Examples** | E. coli, Pseudomonas | S. aureus, S. pneumoniae |

### Clinical Features

**Early (Warm) Shock**:
- Warm, flushed skin
- ↑ Cardiac output
- ↓ SVR (vasodilation)
- Tachycardia, tachypnea
- Fever or hypothermia

**Late (Cold) Shock**:
- Cool, clammy skin
- ↓ Cardiac output
- ↑ SVR
- Oliguria, altered mental status
- Multi-organ failure

## Organ Changes in Shock

### Heart
- Subendocardial necrosis (watershed area)
- "Contraction band necrosis" (catecholamine damage)

### Lungs
- **Shock lung / ARDS (Diffuse alveolar damage)**
- Hyaline membranes
- Alveolar edema
- Later: Type II pneumocyte proliferation

### Kidneys
- **Acute tubular necrosis (ATN)**
- Tubular epithelial necrosis (PCT, thick ascending limb)
- Muddy brown casts
- Oliguria → Polyuric recovery phase

### Liver
- Centrilobular necrosis (Zone 3 - furthest from O₂)
- "Shock liver"
- ↑ Transaminases

### Brain
- **Watershed infarcts** (border zones between arterial territories)
- Laminar necrosis (layers 3, 5, 6 of cortex)
- "Respirator brain" if prolonged

### GI Tract
- Mucosal hemorrhage and necrosis
- Stress ulcers
- Bacterial translocation

### Adrenals
- Hemorrhagic necrosis
- **Waterhouse-Friderichsen syndrome** (meningococcemia)

## Cardiogenic Shock

### Causes
- **MI** (most common) - >40% LV damage
- Arrhythmias
- Cardiomyopathy
- Mechanical: VSD, papillary muscle rupture, tamponade

### Features
- ↓ CO, ↑ SVR, ↑ CVP/PCWP
- Pulmonary edema
- Cold, clammy extremities
- Jugular venous distension

## Hypovolemic Shock

### Causes
- **Hemorrhage** (trauma, GI bleed)
- Fluid loss (burns, diarrhea, vomiting)
- Third spacing (pancreatitis, ascites)

### Compensation
| Blood Loss | Stage | Features |
|------------|-------|----------|
| <15% | Class I | Minimal symptoms |
| 15-30% | Class II | Tachycardia, ↓ pulse pressure |
| 30-40% | Class III | Tachycardia, hypotension, confusion |
| >40% | Class IV | Severe shock, altered consciousness |

## Anaphylactic Shock

### Mechanism
\`\`\`
Previous sensitization → IgE on mast cells
    ↓
Re-exposure to allergen
    ↓
Mast cell degranulation
    ↓
Histamine, leukotrienes, prostaglandins
    ↓
├── Vasodilation
├── ↑ Vascular permeability
├── Bronchoconstriction
└── ↑ Mucus secretion
    ↓
Distributive shock
\`\`\`

### Treatment
- **Epinephrine** (α1 vasoconstriction, β2 bronchodilation)
- Airway management
- Fluids, antihistamines, steroids

## Neurogenic Shock

### Mechanism
- Loss of sympathetic tone (spinal cord injury, anesthesia)
- Vasodilation + bradycardia
- "Warm" shock

### Features
- Hypotension WITHOUT compensatory tachycardia
- Warm, dry skin (no sympathetic response)
- Bradycardia (vagal unopposed)`,
      keyPoints: [
        'Septic shock = most common cause of death from shock; cytokine storm (TNF, IL-1, IL-6)',
        'Early septic shock = warm (↑CO, ↓SVR); Late = cold (↓CO, ↑SVR)',
        'Cardiogenic: ↓CO, ↑SVR, ↑PCWP; Hypovolemic: ↓CO, ↑SVR, ↓CVP',
        'Shock stages: Compensated → Progressive → Irreversible',
        'Shock lung = ARDS/Diffuse alveolar damage (hyaline membranes)',
        'Shock kidney = ATN (muddy brown casts)',
        'Shock liver = centrilobular necrosis (Zone 3)',
        'Waterhouse-Friderichsen = adrenal hemorrhage in meningococcemia'
      ],
