  // NEOPLASIA - GENERAL CONCEPTS
  // =============================================================================
  {
    id: 'neoplasia-general',
    subjectId: 'pathology',
    subspecialtyId: 'pathology-general',
    name: 'Neoplasia - General Concepts',
    slug: 'neoplasia-general',
    description: 'Benign vs malignant, nomenclature, grading, staging',
    content: {
      concept: `# Neoplasia - General Concepts

## Definition

> **Neoplasia** literally means "new growth." A **neoplasm** is an abnormal mass of tissue with growth that exceeds and is uncoordinated with normal tissues and persists after cessation of the stimuli that evoked the change.

> "A neoplasm is an abnormal mass of tissue, the growth of which exceeds and is uncoordinated with that of normal tissues, and persists in the same excessive manner after cessation of the stimulus which evoked the change." - Willis

## Nomenclature

### Benign Tumors

| Tissue Type | Benign Tumor |
|-------------|--------------|
| **Epithelial** - Squamous | Squamous papilloma |
| **Epithelial** - Glandular | Adenoma |
| **Epithelial** - Surface | Papilloma |
| **Connective** - Fibrous | Fibroma |
| **Connective** - Cartilage | Chondroma |
| **Connective** - Bone | Osteoma |
| **Connective** - Fat | Lipoma |
| **Connective** - Smooth muscle | Leiomyoma |
| **Connective** - Skeletal muscle | Rhabdomyoma |
| **Connective** - Blood vessels | Hemangioma |

### Malignant Tumors

| Tissue Type | Malignant Tumor |
|-------------|-----------------|
| **Epithelial** - Squamous | Squamous cell carcinoma |
| **Epithelial** - Glandular | Adenocarcinoma |
| **Connective** - Fibrous | Fibrosarcoma |
| **Connective** - Cartilage | Chondrosarcoma |
| **Connective** - Bone | Osteosarcoma |
| **Connective** - Fat | Liposarcoma |
| **Connective** - Smooth muscle | Leiomyosarcoma |
| **Connective** - Skeletal muscle | Rhabdomyosarcoma |
| **Connective** - Blood vessels | Angiosarcoma |

### Exceptions to Nomenclature Rules

\`\`\`
MALIGNANT but end in "-oma":
├── Melanoma (melanocyte origin)
├── Lymphoma (lymphoid origin)
├── Seminoma (germ cell)
├── Hepatoma (hepatocellular carcinoma)
├── Mesothelioma
└── Glioma (astrocytoma, etc.)

OTHER SPECIAL NAMES:
├── Blastomas: Embryonal tumors (nephroblastoma, neuroblastoma)
├── Teratomas: Multiple germ layers (benign or malignant)
└── Hamartomas: Disorganized normal tissue (not true neoplasm)
\`\`\`

> 💎 Remember: Lymphoma, Melanoma, Seminoma, Mesothelioma are MALIGNANT despite "-oma" suffix

### Mixed Tumors

| Tumor | Components | Location |
|-------|------------|----------|
| **Pleomorphic adenoma** | Epithelial + Myxoid stroma | Salivary gland |
| **Fibroadenoma** | Epithelial + Fibrous stroma | Breast |
| **Teratoma** | All 3 germ layers | Gonads, mediastinum |
| **Wilms tumor** | Blastema + Epithelium + Stroma | Kidney |

## Benign vs Malignant

### Key Differences

| Feature | Benign | Malignant |
|---------|--------|-----------|
| **Differentiation** | Well differentiated | Variable (well → anaplastic) |
| **Growth rate** | Slow | Rapid (usually) |
| **Local invasion** | Expansile, encapsulated | Infiltrative, destructive |
| **Metastasis** | Absent | Present |
| **Necrosis** | Rare | Common (outgrows blood supply) |
| **Mitoses** | Few, normal | Many, abnormal |
| **Effect on host** | Local compression | Cachexia, paraneoplastic |

### Differentiation & Anaplasia

**Differentiation** = extent to which tumor cells resemble their normal counterparts

**Anaplasia** = lack of differentiation (hallmark of malignancy)

**Features of Anaplasia**:
\`\`\`
├── Pleomorphism (variation in size/shape)
├── Abnormal nuclear morphology
│   ├── Hyperchromatism
│   ├── ↑ Nuclear:Cytoplasmic ratio (1:1 vs normal 1:4-6)
│   └── Irregular nuclear membrane
├── Atypical mitoses (tripolar, multipolar)
├── Loss of polarity (disorganized architecture)
└── Giant cells (tumor giant cells ≠ foreign body)
\`\`\`

### Dysplasia

> **Dysplasia** = disordered growth with loss of cellular uniformity and architectural orientation

- Preneoplastic but NOT cancer
- Does NOT inevitably progress to cancer
- Confined to epithelium (above basement membrane)
- **Carcinoma in situ (CIS)** = full-thickness dysplasia

\`\`\`
Normal → Mild Dysplasia → Moderate → Severe → CIS → Invasive Carcinoma
                                         ↑
                                    (Full thickness)
\`\`\`

## Metastasis

> **Metastasis** = spread of tumor to sites physically discontinuous with primary tumor - DEFINITIVE evidence of malignancy

### Routes of Metastasis

**1. Lymphatic Spread**
- Most common route for CARCINOMAS
- Follows natural lymphatic drainage
- Sentinel lymph node = first node receiving drainage
- Example: Breast CA → Axillary nodes

**2. Hematogenous Spread**
- Most common route for SARCOMAS
- Veins more easily invaded than arteries
- **Liver and Lungs** most common sites (portal and caval drainage)
- Common patterns:
  - GI cancers → Liver (portal)
  - All others → Lungs (caval)
  - Lung/Liver → Anywhere

**3. Direct Seeding (Transcoelomic)**
- Spread within body cavities
- Ovarian CA → Peritoneum
- Lung CA → Pleura

### Common Metastatic Patterns

\`\`\`
PRIMARY TUMOR          →    COMMON METASTATIC SITES
Prostate               →    Bone (osteoblastic)
Breast                 →    Bone, Lung, Liver, Brain
Lung                   →    Brain, Bone, Liver, Adrenal
Colorectal             →    Liver, Lung
Kidney (RCC)           →    Lung, Bone
Melanoma               →    Anywhere (unpredictable)
Thyroid (follicular)   →    Lung, Bone
\`\`\`

> 💎 **"Seed and Soil"** hypothesis: Metastasis requires favorable microenvironment

### Exceptions - Benign Tumors That Metastasize
- Leiomyoma of uterus → Lungs (benign metastasizing leiomyoma)
- Hydatidiform mole → Lungs

## Grading and Staging

### Grading

> Based on **histologic appearance** (differentiation, mitoses, architecture)

**General Grading**:
| Grade | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| **G1** | Well differentiated |
| **G2** | Moderately differentiated |
| **G3** | Poorly differentiated |
| **G4** | Undifferentiated (anaplastic) |

**Specific Grading Systems**:
- Gleason score (prostate)
- Bloom-Richardson (breast)
- Fuhrman (renal cell carcinoma)

### Staging

> Based on **extent of spread** (size, lymph nodes, metastasis)

**TNM System**:
\`\`\`
T = Primary Tumor size/extent
    T0: No primary
    Tis: Carcinoma in situ
    T1-4: Increasing size/local invasion

N = Regional Lymph Nodes
    N0: No nodal involvement
    N1-3: Increasing nodal involvement

M = Distant Metastasis
    M0: No metastasis
    M1: Distant metastasis present
\`\`\`

**Stage Grouping**:
| Stage | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| **Stage I** | Localized, small tumor |
| **Stage II** | Larger tumor, limited spread |
| **Stage III** | Regional lymph node involvement |
| **Stage IV** | Distant metastasis |

> 💎 **Staging is more important than grading** for prognosis

## Effects of Tumors on Host

### Local Effects
- Mass effect, compression
- Obstruction (bowel, bile duct, ureter)
- Ulceration and bleeding
- Functional (hormone-secreting adenomas)

### Systemic Effects - Cancer Cachexia
- Weight loss, muscle wasting
- Anorexia, weakness
- Mediated by TNF-α ("cachectin"), IL-1, IL-6, IFN-γ
- NOT explained by caloric intake

### Paraneoplastic Syndromes

| Syndrome | Tumor | Mechanism |
|----------|-------|-----------|
| **Hypercalcemia** | Squamous lung, breast, renal | PTHrP |
| **SIADH** | Small cell lung | Ectopic ADH |
| **Cushing syndrome** | Small cell lung | Ectopic ACTH |
| **Polycythemia** | RCC, hepatoma, hemangioblastoma | Ectopic EPO |
| **Acanthosis nigricans** | GI malignancies | ? |
| **Lambert-Eaton** | Small cell lung | Anti-Ca channel Ab |
| **Dermatomyositis** | Various | ? |

> 💎 **Small cell lung cancer** = most common cause of paraneoplastic syndromes`,
