    content: {
      concept: `# Carcinogenesis

## Overview

> **Carcinogenesis** is the multistep process by which normal cells acquire the characteristics of cancer. It involves **accumulation of mutations** in genes controlling cell growth, differentiation, and death.

## Hallmarks of Cancer

\`\`\`
THE 10 HALLMARKS OF CANCER (Hanahan & Weinberg):

1. SUSTAINING PROLIFERATIVE SIGNALING
   └── Oncogenes (RAS, MYC, growth factors)

2. EVADING GROWTH SUPPRESSORS
   └── Inactivate tumor suppressors (RB, p53)

3. RESISTING CELL DEATH
   └── ↑ BCL-2, ↓ p53

4. ENABLING REPLICATIVE IMMORTALITY
   └── Telomerase activation

5. INDUCING ANGIOGENESIS
   └── VEGF, FGF

6. ACTIVATING INVASION & METASTASIS
   └── E-cadherin loss, MMPs

7. REPROGRAMMING ENERGY METABOLISM
   └── Warburg effect (aerobic glycolysis)

8. EVADING IMMUNE DESTRUCTION
   └── PD-L1, immunosuppressive cytokines

9. GENOME INSTABILITY & MUTATION
   └── DNA repair defects

10. TUMOR-PROMOTING INFLAMMATION
    └── Cytokines, ROS
\`\`\`

## Classes of Cancer Genes

### Oncogenes (Proto-oncogenes → Oncogenes)

> **Oncogenes** = mutated/overexpressed versions of normal genes (proto-oncogenes) that promote cell proliferation

**Activation Mechanisms**:
\`\`\`
1. POINT MUTATION
   └── RAS (single nucleotide change)

2. GENE AMPLIFICATION
   └── MYC, HER2/neu, NMYC

3. CHROMOSOMAL TRANSLOCATION
   ├── t(9;22) BCR-ABL (CML)
   ├── t(8;14) MYC (Burkitt)
   └── t(14;18) BCL-2 (Follicular lymphoma)

4. INSERTIONAL MUTAGENESIS
   └── Viral integration (HPV, HBV)
\`\`\`

**Major Oncogenes**:

| Oncogene | Function | Cancer |
|----------|----------|--------|
| **RAS** | G-protein (GTPase) | Colon, pancreas, lung (30% of all cancers) |
| **MYC** | Transcription factor | Burkitt lymphoma t(8;14) |
| **HER2/ERBB2** | Growth factor receptor | Breast (25%) |
| **ABL** | Tyrosine kinase | CML t(9;22) |
| **BCL-2** | Anti-apoptotic | Follicular lymphoma t(14;18) |
| **BRAF** | Serine/threonine kinase | Melanoma, colon |
| **RET** | Receptor tyrosine kinase | MEN2, medullary thyroid CA |
| **KIT** | Receptor tyrosine kinase | GIST |

> 💎 **RAS** is the most commonly mutated oncogene (~30% of all human cancers)

### Tumor Suppressor Genes

> **Tumor suppressor genes** normally inhibit cell proliferation; BOTH alleles must be inactivated ("two-hit hypothesis")

**Two-Hit Hypothesis (Knudson)**:
\`\`\`
SPORADIC CANCER:           HEREDITARY CANCER:
Normal cell                Normal cell
    ↓ 1st hit (somatic)        ↓ (already has 1 mutant allele)
Carrier cell               Carrier cell (all cells)
    ↓ 2nd hit (somatic)        ↓ 2nd hit (somatic)
Cancer                     Cancer (earlier, multiple)
\`\`\`

**Major Tumor Suppressors**:

| Gene | Function | Cancer |
|------|----------|--------|
| **RB** | Cell cycle control (G1→S) | Retinoblastoma, osteosarcoma |
| **p53** | "Guardian of genome" | Most common (>50% of cancers) |
| **APC** | Wnt pathway inhibitor | Familial adenomatous polyposis |
| **BRCA1/2** | DNA repair (HR) | Breast, ovarian |
| **WT1** | Transcription factor | Wilms tumor |
| **NF1** | RAS inhibitor (GAP) | Neurofibromatosis type 1 |
| **NF2** | Merlin (cytoskeleton) | Neurofibromatosis type 2 |
| **VHL** | HIF regulation | Renal cell carcinoma |

> 💎 **p53** is the most commonly mutated gene in human cancers

### RB and Cell Cycle Control

\`\`\`
G1 CHECKPOINT:
                    CDK4/6
Mitogens → Cyclin D ────→ RB-P (inactive)
                              ↓
                         E2F released
                              ↓
                         S phase entry

p53 → p21 ─┤ CDK4/6 (inhibits)

RB mutations → Uncontrolled E2F → Uncontrolled S phase entry
\`\`\`

### p53 - Guardian of the Genome

**Functions of p53**:
\`\`\`
DNA DAMAGE
    ↓
p53 activation (stabilization)
    ↓
├── G1 ARREST (p21 → inhibits CDKs)
│   └── Time for DNA repair
│
├── DNA REPAIR
│   └── GADD45 activation
│
├── APOPTOSIS (if damage irreparable)
│   └── BAX, PUMA, NOXA (pro-apoptotic)
│
└── SENESCENCE
    └── Permanent arrest
\`\`\`

**p53 Inactivation**:
- Mutation (most common mechanism)
- MDM2 amplification (inhibits p53)
- HPV E6 protein (degrades p53)

### APC/β-Catenin Pathway

\`\`\`
NORMAL:
Wnt signal absent → APC/Axin complex → β-catenin degradation

APC MUTATED (FAP):
No APC → β-catenin accumulates → Enters nucleus → MYC, Cyclin D
→ Proliferation
\`\`\`

## Chemical Carcinogens

### Types of Chemical Carcinogens

**1. Direct-Acting Carcinogens**:
- No metabolic activation needed
- Alkylating agents: Cyclophosphamide, nitrogen mustard
- Acylating agents

**2. Indirect-Acting (Pro-carcinogens)**:
- Require metabolic activation (mainly by CYP450)

| Pro-carcinogen | Activated By | Cancer |
|----------------|--------------|--------|
| **Aflatoxin B1** | CYP450 | Hepatocellular carcinoma |
| **Benzo[a]pyrene** | CYP450 | Lung, skin |
| **Nitrosamines** | Stomach acid | Gastric cancer |
| **Vinyl chloride** | CYP450 | Angiosarcoma of liver |
| **Aromatic amines** | CYP450 | Bladder (β-naphthylamine) |
| **Benzene** | CYP450 | Leukemia |

> 💎 **Aflatoxin B1** (Aspergillus flavus) + HBV = synergistic for hepatocellular carcinoma

### Stages of Chemical Carcinogenesis

\`\`\`
INITIATION          PROMOTION           PROGRESSION
(Irreversible)      (Reversible)        (Irreversible)
    ↓                   ↓                   ↓
DNA damage         Clonal expansion    Malignant phenotype
(permanent)        (requires promoter)  (genomic instability)
    ↓                   ↓                   ↓
Single cell        Benign neoplasm     Invasive cancer
\`\`\`

## Radiation Carcinogenesis

### Ionizing Radiation

**Mechanism**: DNA damage (double-strand breaks)

| Radiation Type | Cancer |
|----------------|--------|
| **X-rays** | Leukemia, thyroid, breast, lung |
| **Nuclear fallout** | Thyroid (I-131), Leukemia |
| **Therapeutic radiation** | Sarcomas, leukemia (secondary) |

### UV Radiation

**Mechanism**: Pyrimidine dimers → if not repaired by NER → mutations

**Spectrum**:
- UVB (280-320 nm): Most carcinogenic
- UVA (320-400 nm): Deeper penetration

**Cancers**:
- Basal cell carcinoma
- Squamous cell carcinoma
- Melanoma

**Xeroderma Pigmentosum**:
- Defective nucleotide excision repair (NER)
- >1000-fold ↑ skin cancer risk
- Autosomal recessive

## Viral Carcinogenesis

### DNA Viruses

| Virus | Cancer | Mechanism |
|-------|--------|-----------|
| **HPV** (16, 18) | Cervical, anal, oropharyngeal | E6 → p53 degradation, E7 → RB inactivation |
| **EBV** | Burkitt, nasopharyngeal, Hodgkin | LMP1 (NF-κB), EBNA |
| **HBV** | Hepatocellular carcinoma | HBx protein, chronic inflammation |
| **HHV-8** | Kaposi sarcoma, PEL | GPCR, viral cyclins |

### RNA Viruses

| Virus | Cancer | Mechanism |
|-------|--------|-----------|
| **HTLV-1** | Adult T-cell leukemia | Tax protein (NF-κB) |
| **HCV** | Hepatocellular carcinoma | Chronic inflammation, cirrhosis |

### HPV Oncogenic Mechanism

\`\`\`
HPV 16/18 (High-risk)
    ↓
Integration into host genome
    ↓
├── E6 protein → Binds p53 → Ubiquitination → Degradation
│                           (via E6AP)
│
└── E7 protein → Binds RB → Releases E2F → Uncontrolled proliferation
\`\`\`

> 💎 **E6 = p53 killer, E7 = RB killer**

### Helicobacter pylori (Bacterial)

- **Gastric adenocarcinoma** (intestinal type)
- **MALT lymphoma** (B-cell)
- Mechanism: Chronic inflammation, CagA protein (oncoprotein)
- Only bacterial carcinogen definitively linked to cancer

## Hereditary Cancer Syndromes

| Syndrome | Gene | Inheritance | Cancers |
|----------|------|-------------|---------|
| **Li-Fraumeni** | p53 | AD | Sarcomas, breast, brain, leukemia |
| **FAP** | APC | AD | Colorectal (100% by age 40) |
| **HNPCC (Lynch)** | MSH2, MLH1 | AD | Colorectal, endometrial |
| **Hereditary Breast** | BRCA1/2 | AD | Breast, ovarian |
| **Retinoblastoma** | RB | AD | Retinoblastoma, osteosarcoma |
| **MEN1** | MEN1 | AD | Pituitary, parathyroid, pancreas |
| **MEN2** | RET | AD | Medullary thyroid, pheo |
| **VHL** | VHL | AD | RCC, hemangioblastoma, pheo |
| **Xeroderma Pigmentosum** | NER genes | AR | Skin cancers |

> 💎 **Li-Fraumeni** (p53) = SBLA syndrome: Sarcoma, Breast, Leukemia, Adrenal`,
      keyPoints: [
